{"link": "https://www.marketwatch.com/story/dow-jones-industrial-average-rebounds-powered-by-nike-and-microsoft-2018-02-09", "source": "https://www.marketwatch.com/", "text": "Published: Still, the blue-chip index is down 9.1% from its intraday record high on Jan. 26 By The Dow Jones Industrial Average rebounded by 1.4% on Friday, with all but four of 30 companies rising. The gains were led by Nike. The S&P 500 Index was up 1.5%, driven by Mattel. The Dow Jones Industrial Average closed at 24,190.90, producing a decline of 9.1% from its intraday record high of 26,616.71 on Jan. 26. The S&P 500 closed at 2,619.55 and was down 8.8% from its intraday record high of 2,872.87, also on Jan. 26.     Information technology \u2014 last year\u2019s hottest sector \u2014 was strongest on Friday. The best sector this month has been consumer discretionary, with a 2.2% gain, while all other sectors have posted declines. The worst sector of February has been energy, with an 11.3% decline.      Philip van Doorn covers various investment and industry topics.  He has previously worked as a senior analyst at TheStreet.com. He also has experience in community banking and as a credit analyst at the Federal Home Loan Bank of New York. Philip van Doorn covers various investment and industry topics.  He has previously worked as a senior analyst at TheStreet.com. He also has experience in community banking and as a credit analyst at the Federal Home Loan Bank of New York. Join the conversation Copyright \u00a9 2018 MarketWatch, Inc.  All rights reserved. By using this site you agree to the , , and .", "tick": "NVDA", "headline": "Dow Jones Industrial Average rebounds, powered by Nike and Microsoft - MarketWatch", "author": "Philip van Doorn"}
{"link": "https://www.marketwatch.com/story/eye-popping-nvidia-earnings-send-stock-soaring-but-automotive-business-still-stalled-2018-02-08", "source": "https://www.marketwatch.com/", "text": "Published: Opinion: Gaming and server businesses are living up to the hype, but self-driving-car sales are still in the future By Nvidia Corp. reported full-year earnings Thursday that validated the huge increase in its stock price over the past two-plus years, but the final piece of the bull theory is still in neutral until at least later this year. Nvidia\u2019s numbers were eye-popping, especially for a company that has been public for nearly 20 years and experienced an annual sales decline just five years ago. The key numbers for Nvidia\u2019s 2018 fiscal year: , profit increased 83% (yes, that\u2019s GAAP) and gross margin increased by 110 basis points. Those numbers were just part of , which sent shares up more than 7% in late trading. Nvidia stock has already gained 83.4% in the past year, while the Dow Jones Industrial Average increased 23.9%, and that rise came on top of the biggest gains on the S&P 500 index in 2016. Nvidia\u2019s ride has been fueled by greater demand for its core product, graphics chips, which have found a home beyond videogames thanks to their usefulness in machine learning. The general bull theory is that Nvidia\u2019s core gaming business will continue to grow thanks to the rise of esports and more graphically-intense videogames, while new businesses selling chips for servers and autonomous cars will eventually be huge. With its fourth-quarter report, Nvidia lived up to two parts of that theory. The core gaming business, which has been boosted by demands for those same chips , grew nearly 36% to more than $5.5 billion in revenue, more than Nvidia\u2019s revenue total in any year before the previous one. The server business, meanwhile, came close to $2 billion in annual revenue, after failing to touch $1 billion the year before and mostly failing to exist before that. The one laggard so far is the automotive business, which declined sequentially in the fourth quarter and grew less than 15% for the full year. The results were below analysts\u2019 average expectations for the second quarter in a row. Chief Financial Officer Colette Kress said on a conference call Thursday that Nvidia automotive sales fell as its ditches a longtime business of providing chips that power in-car systems to next-generation auto supplies. \u201cThe sequential decline reflects our transition from infotainment, which is becoming commoditized, to next-generation AI cockpit systems and complete top-to-bottom self-driving-vehicle platforms built on Nvidia hardware and software,\u201d Kress said. Nvidia , including a focus on and new in-car experiences involving augmented reality. Based on Thursday\u2019s commentary, we may see Nvidia\u2019s auto business struggle a bit before they realize any gains from their plans for the future. The Xavier processor, a chip with 9 billion transistors that Nvidia calls the most complex system-on-a-chip ever created, is expected to eventually drive its automotive business. It will act as the heart of its Nvidia Drive ecosystem, a platform it has developed for car makers to use to create safe self-driving cars. Nvidia Chief Executive Jensen Huang told analysts that he believes the really big revenue from automotive will begin in about 2019 to 2020, when auto makers, startups, taxi companies, ride-hailing companies and others begin to order self-driving capabilities in their vehicles and fleets. He revealed that the brains for self-driving cars will sell for an average of about $500 to $1,000, while those for \u201crobo-taxis,\u201d as Nvidia refers to autonomous ride-hailing vehicles, will command several thousand dollars each. The upside for Nvidia\u2019s automotive business is expected to come from software, bigger volumes of its chips and for self-driving cars. Stacy Rasgon, a Bernstein Research analyst, wrote in a recent note that he expects growth in automotive \u201cto come from software development agreements related to autonomous driving at some point this year,\u201d he said. Investors who have bought into Nvidia are reaping rewards from gaming, cryptocurrency and a booming server business right now, but the automotive business still needs some gas. If that business is as big as Nvidia has claimed, shares could keep driving higher. Join the conversation Copyright \u00a9 2018 MarketWatch, Inc.  All rights reserved. By using this site you agree to the , , and .", "tick": "NVDA", "headline": "Eye-popping Nvidia earnings send stock soaring, but automotive business still stalled - MarketWatch", "author": "Therese Poletti, Jeremy C. Owens"}
